     {
       "category": "tips",
       "content": "A Claude Project's custom-instructions box is three short fields most people leave near-empty. Filling them well is the move that separates a Project from a folder of one-off chats. The pilot hub's worked example, for a Partner University Updates Project, sets the pattern.\n\n\"You help draft communications to our 13 university partner admissions contacts. Tone is collegial and supportive — these are year-round relationships. Always include specific dates and next steps. Never reference individual student names or financial details.\"\n\nThree sentences, three loads. The first names the audience and the relationship: who Claude is talking to and on what footing. The second encodes what good output looks like: dates, next steps, the working standards your team already uses. The third sets the governance line: no student names, no financial details, the Tier 3 data tier baked into the workspace.\n\nThe same shape scales. A coach's \"Cohort Check-In\" Project might read: \"You help me draft outreach to first-generation scholars at [partner]. Tone is direct and warm. Always offer one concrete next step. Never reference grades or family details.\" A development \"Funder Update\" Project: \"You help draft donor stewardship to lead-tier funders. Tone matches our last impact report. Always tie a scholar outcome to the funder's investment area. Never share aggregate metrics that haven't appeared in a published source.\"\n\nThree sentences, every Project. The hour spent writing them is the hour your team stops re-explaining context the next time the work shows up.",
